P(slug="techno-101-india", date="2026-01-10", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Techno 101: how India learned to love the four-on-the-floor",
  excerpt="Repetitive, hypnotic and built for the long haul — a beginner's guide to the sound powering India's underground.",
  tags=["techno","underground","guide"],
  body="""<p>Techno is the sound of India's underground, and if you've ever wondered why a room full of people will happily dance to what seems like the same beat for two hours, this is your explainer. Techno isn't about the hook — it's about the hypnosis.</p>
<h2>What it actually is</h2>
<p>At its core, techno is a steady four-on-the-floor kick, stripped-back percussion, and a slow, patient build of tension and texture over time. There's rarely a vocal chorus or an obvious drop. The pleasure is in the groove — the way small changes ripple through a repetitive framework until you stop thinking and just move.</p>
<h2>Why it works on a dancefloor</h2>
<p>Techno rewards commitment. The first twenty minutes might feel minimal; then the set locks in and time disappears. That's the famous "heads-down" state — the whole point of a good techno night. It's music designed for the dancefloor first and the headphones second.</p>
<h2>The India context</h2>
<p>Bengaluru, Goa, Mumbai and pockets of every metro have built serious techno communities, and the sound anchors our own OFFGRID and Hypnotica nights in Udaipur. If you're used to Bollywood and commercial floors, techno is a different discipline — go in patient, stay past the warm-up, and let it take you somewhere.</p>""")

P(slug="afro-house-india", date="2026-01-14", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Afro house: the sound quietly taking over India's outdoor floors",
  excerpt="Melodic, percussive and made for open air — why afro house has become the heartbeat of the Indian party scene.",
  tags=["afro house","outdoor","guide"],
  body="""<p>If you've been to an outdoor party in India in the last couple of years, you've heard afro house — even if you didn't know its name. Warm, melodic, drenched in percussion and built for open skies, it has become one of the most popular sounds on the country's dancefloors.</p>
<h2>The sound</h2>
<p>Afro house blends the four-on-the-floor structure of house music with African percussion, chant-like vocals and rich, emotional melodies. It's less aggressive than techno and more soulful than commercial EDM — a sound that feels organic and human, which is exactly why it works so well outdoors and in the daytime.</p>
<h2>Why India took to it</h2>
<p>The percussive, celebratory quality of afro house sits comfortably next to Indian musical sensibilities, and its melodic warmth makes it accessible even to crowds who don't consider themselves underground. It bridges the gap between the pure techno heads and the wider party crowd — perfect for pool parties, sundowners and lakeside nights.</p>
<h2>Where to hear it</h2>
<p>Afro house anchors a growing share of India's outdoor programming, and it's central to what we do at OFFGRID. If techno feels too stark for you, afro house is the way in — same underground credibility, far more melody.</p>""")

P(slug="house-music-explained", date="2026-01-18", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="House music, explained: the genre everything else grew out of",
  excerpt="Before techno, before EDM, there was house. A guide to the foundational sound of club culture — and its Indian life.",
  tags=["house","guide","history"],
  body="""<p>House is the granddaddy of dance music — the Chicago-born genre from which almost everything on a modern dancefloor descends. Understanding house is understanding the DNA of club culture itself, and it remains one of the most versatile sounds you'll hear out.</p>
<h2>The essence</h2>
<p>House is built on a warm four-on-the-floor beat, soulful vocals or samples, and a groove that's more about feel than intensity. It spans a huge range — deep house is mellow and hypnotic, tech house pushes toward the club's harder edge, and soulful and vocal house lean into emotion and melody.</p>
<h2>Why it endures</h2>
<p>House is endlessly adaptable. It can soundtrack a sunset lounge or a peak-time club, a rooftop or a warehouse. That flexibility is why, decades after it began, house is still the backbone of the global scene — and increasingly of India's.</p>
<h2>On Indian floors</h2>
<p>Tech house and deep house have huge followings in Mumbai, Bengaluru and Goa, and the sound blends beautifully with the afro house wave. For newcomers, house is the friendliest entry into underground dance music — groovy, warm and immediately danceable.</p>""")

P(slug="goa-trance-psytrance-india", date="2026-01-26", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Goa trance and psytrance: India's original electronic export",
  excerpt="Long before EDM, the beaches of Goa birthed a global genre. The story of psytrance and its enduring Indian home.",
  tags=["psytrance","Goa","history","guide"],
  body="""<p>Here's a fact that surprises people: India gave the world an entire electronic genre. Goa trance — and the psytrance that grew from it — was born on the beaches and in the full-moon parties of Goa in the late 20th century, and it remains one of the country's most distinctive musical legacies.</p>
<h2>The sound</h2>
<p>Psytrance is fast, hypnotic and intensely psychedelic — rolling basslines, swirling synths and a relentless tempo designed to send dancers into a trance state over long, marathon sets. It's the original sunrise music, made for parties that run from dusk deep into the next day.</p>
<h2>The culture</h2>
<p>The Goa scene created a whole ethos — outdoor, communal, spiritual, and fiercely dedicated to the dancefloor as a place of transcendence. That culture migrated into the Himalayan party scene too, where Kasol, Manali and the Parvati Valley keep the psytrance flame burning every summer.</p>
<h2>Still going</h2>
<p>While techno and house now dominate the fashionable end of the scene, psytrance has a devoted, unbroken following in India. It's a reminder that the country isn't just importing global dance culture — it helped write it.</p>""")

P(slug="bollywood-nights-desi-dancefloor", date="2026-02-03", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="The Bollywood night: India's own dancefloor, and why it always wins",
  excerpt="No genre fills a room in India like Bollywood. An appreciation of the singalong party that beats every import.",
  tags=["Bollywood","commercial","guide"],
  body="""<p>You can book the best techno DJ in the world, but in most of India, nothing fills a dancefloor like a well-programmed Bollywood night. It's the country's own sound, its shared language, and the reason our Bollywood Nite series is one of Pronite's biggest draws.</p>
<h2>Why it works</h2>
<p>Bollywood music is built for collective joy. Everyone knows the words. The songs are engineered for celebration — big hooks, danceable rhythms, decades of nostalgia baked in. A Bollywood floor isn't watching the DJ; it's singing at the top of its lungs, and that shared energy is impossible to manufacture with any imported genre.</p>
<h2>The craft</h2>
<p>A great Bollywood set is deceptively skilled. It moves between eras — 90s classics, 2000s dancefloor anthems, current chartbusters — reads the crowd's nostalgia, and blends tracks cleanly enough to keep the energy unbroken. Add dhol breaks at the right moments and the room goes up.</p>
<h2>The verdict</h2>
<p>Underground has its place, but the Bollywood night is India's home advantage. It's inclusive, euphoric and endlessly reliable — and when it's done right, there's no better party in the country.</p>""")

P(slug="edm-big-room-india", date="2026-02-07", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="EDM in India: the big-room boom that opened the floodgates",
  excerpt="Festival main-stage EDM introduced a generation to dance music. Where it stands now, and what it built.",
  tags=["EDM","festival","guide"],
  body="""<p>For a huge share of India's current party crowd, the gateway drug was big-room EDM — the euphoric, drop-heavy, main-stage festival sound that exploded across the country and turned dance music into a mainstream youth obsession.</p>
<h2>The boom</h2>
<p>The 2010s festival wave — driven by massive events and touring superstar DJs — did something profound: it made electronic music aspirational and accessible to millions of young Indians at once. Big-room EDM, with its huge builds and cathartic drops, was the perfect introduction — immediate, emotional and impossible to ignore.</p>
<h2>Where it is now</h2>
<p>As the crowd matured, tastes fragmented. Many of those early EDM fans moved toward techno, house and afro house, seeking something deeper. But big-room and commercial EDM still command the biggest festival main stages and the largest single-artist shows — it remains the sound of the spectacle.</p>
<h2>The legacy</h2>
<p>Whatever the purists say, EDM built the audience. The thriving underground of today exists because a generation first fell in love with dance music on a festival main stage. That's a legacy worth respecting.</p>""")

P(slug="commercial-vs-underground", date="2026-02-11", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Commercial vs underground: India's two dancefloors, explained",
  excerpt="Bollywood and big-room on one side, techno and house on the other. A guide to the divide — and why you need both.",
  tags=["culture","guide","underground"],
  body="""<p>Spend enough time in India's nightlife and you'll notice it runs on two parallel tracks — the commercial floor and the underground floor. They attract different crowds, demand different things from a DJ, and often can't stand each other. The truth is a healthy scene needs both.</p>
<h2>The commercial floor</h2>
<p>Bollywood, Punjabi pop, big-room EDM and chart hits. This is music for recognition and celebration — the crowd wants to sing, to know every track, to lose themselves in shared nostalgia. It fills the biggest rooms in the country and pays the bills that keep venues alive.</p>
<h2>The underground floor</h2>
<p>Techno, house, afro house, deep electronic. Here the crowd comes for the journey, not the hits — patient sets, unfamiliar tracks, and a dancefloor built on trust in the DJ. Smaller, more devoted, and the source of the scene's credibility and evolution.</p>
<h2>Why both matter</h2>
<p>The commercial side brings the numbers and the energy; the underground brings the depth and the artistry. At Pronite we deliberately run both — Bollywood nights and OFFGRID techno — because a real scene isn't one or the other. It's a city that can do both well.</p>""")

P(slug="bass-music-india", date="2026-02-15", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Bass music in India: dubstep, drum & bass and the low-end faithful",
  excerpt="Heavier, faster and more aggressive — a guide to India's committed bass-music underground.",
  tags=["bass","dubstep","drum and bass","guide"],
  body="""<p>Not everyone wants a groove — some people want to feel the floor shake. Bass music, spanning dubstep, drum &amp; bass and their many mutations, has a smaller but fiercely loyal following in India, and it's some of the most physically intense music you can experience live.</p>
<h2>The family</h2>
<p><b>Dubstep</b> is built on massive, wobbling low-end and half-time drops — heavy, aggressive and cathartic. <b>Drum &amp; bass</b> is its faster cousin, all breakneck breakbeats and rolling sub-bass, demanding serious stamina from a dancer. Together they form the harder-edged wing of India's electronic scene.</p>
<h2>The Indian scene</h2>
<p>Homegrown bass artists and a dedicated network of promoters have kept the sound alive across the metros, and India has produced globally recognised talent in this space. The crowd is younger, more energetic, and there for the sheer physical thrill of a big sound system pushed to its limits.</p>
<h2>Worth trying</h2>
<p>If techno feels too restrained and commercial feels too safe, bass music is the adrenaline option. Find a night with a proper rig and experience it the way it's meant to be felt — in your chest.</p>""")

P(slug="melodic-techno-progressive-india", date="2026-02-19", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Melodic techno and progressive: the emotional end of the underground",
  excerpt="Cinematic, euphoric and deeply popular in India — why melodic techno bridges the head and the heart.",
  tags=["melodic techno","progressive","guide"],
  body="""<p>Somewhere between the starkness of pure techno and the accessibility of house sits melodic techno — and in India, it might be the most beloved underground sound of all. Cinematic, emotional and built around soaring melodies, it's the genre that converts commercial crowds into underground believers.</p>
<h2>The appeal</h2>
<p>Melodic techno and progressive house keep the driving, hypnotic engine of techno but layer it with lush, emotive melodies and grand, cinematic builds. The result is music that hits both the body and the heart — deep enough for the heads, beautiful enough for everyone else.</p>
<h2>Why India loves it</h2>
<p>Indian audiences have a well-documented love of melody, and melodic techno delivers it without sacrificing underground credibility. The genre's biggest global names draw huge crowds when they tour here, and it's a staple of the country's most emotional dancefloor moments.</p>
<h2>The gateway</h2>
<p>If you're curious about the underground but techno feels cold, melodic techno is the perfect bridge. It's the sound of a sunset turning into a night, and India can't get enough of it.</p>""")

P(slug="desi-hip-hop-scene", date="2026-02-23", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Desi hip-hop: from the streets to the main stage",
  excerpt="India's rap explosion changed the sound of a generation. A guide to the scene reshaping the country's nightlife.",
  tags=["hip-hop","rap","desi","guide"],
  body="""<p>The biggest cultural shift in Indian music this decade isn't electronic — it's hip-hop. Desi rap has gone from underground ciphers and street battles to chart domination, blockbuster soundtracks and festival main stages, and it's increasingly a force on the dancefloor too.</p>
<h2>The rise</h2>
<p>Rooted in the real experiences of India's cities — its neighbourhoods, its struggles, its slang — desi hip-hop found a massive, hungry audience among young Indians who saw themselves in it. What started in Mumbai's chawls and Delhi's streets became a mainstream movement, complete with a hit film that put the whole scene on the national radar.</p>
<h2>On the dancefloor</h2>
<p>Hip-hop nights and desi-rap sets are now a fixture in the metros, drawing crowds who want lyrics and attitude alongside beats. It's a different energy from a techno or Bollywood floor — swagger over hypnosis, words over grooves — and it's pulling a young, engaged audience out to events.</p>
<h2>The read</h2>
<p>Desi hip-hop is the sound of contemporary young India, and its influence on nightlife is only growing. Any promoter reading the culture is paying close attention.</p>""")

P(slug="sufi-indie-fusion-nights", date="2026-02-27", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Sufi, indie and fusion: the softer side of India's night out",
  excerpt="Not every great night is a rave. A guide to the live, soulful and fusion events that fill India's other dancefloor.",
  tags=["Sufi","indie","live music","guide"],
  body="""<p>India's nightlife isn't only DJs and drops. A huge part of the country's going-out culture runs on live music — Sufi nights, indie gigs, ghazal evenings and genre-blending fusion acts that offer something warmer and more contemplative than a club floor.</p>
<h2>The live tradition</h2>
<p>From intimate Sufi performances that can move a room to tears, to the thriving independent-band circuit in cities like Mumbai, Bengaluru and Kolkata, live music holds a special place in Indian nightlife. These are nights built on emotion and craft, where the crowd listens as much as it dances.</p>
<h2>Fusion's moment</h2>
<p>Some of India's most exciting artists blend classical and folk traditions with electronic production, creating a distinctly Indian sound that works on a modern dancefloor without abandoning its roots. It's a genre space the country is uniquely positioned to lead.</p>
<h2>Why it matters</h2>
<p>A complete scene has range — the sweaty techno basement and the soulful live room both belong. For a different kind of night out, seek out the Sufi, indie and fusion events. They're some of the most rewarding shows India has to offer.</p>""")

P(slug="punjabi-pop-dancefloor", date="2026-03-03", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Punjabi pop: the genre that conquered every Indian dancefloor",
  excerpt="From Chandigarh to Canada to the world charts — how Punjabi music became India's default party sound.",
  tags=["Punjabi","commercial","guide"],
  body="""<p>Walk into almost any club in North India — and increasingly the whole country — and the sound filling the floor is Punjabi. Over the last decade, Punjabi pop has gone from a regional genre to a global phenomenon, and on the dancefloor its dominance is total.</p>
<h2>The takeover</h2>
<p>Punjabi music is engineered for celebration: big beats, swaggering hooks, and an irresistible, high-energy bounce. Its stars have become some of the most-streamed artists on the planet, breaking into global charts and collaborating with international names — all while keeping the dancefloor as their home base.</p>
<h2>Why it rules the club</h2>
<p>Like Bollywood, Punjabi pop thrives on recognition and shared euphoria, but with an extra layer of aspirational bravado that the crowd loves to perform. In the North especially — Chandigarh, Delhi, Punjab's cities — it's simply the default sound of a good night.</p>
<h2>The read</h2>
<p>Any DJ working an Indian commercial floor knows the Punjabi block is non-negotiable. It's the genre that reads the room before you do — and it's not slowing down.</p>""")

P(slug="live-vs-dj-sets", date="2026-03-07", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Live act vs DJ set: what's the difference, and which should you go to?",
  excerpt="A quick guide to the two ways electronic music reaches a stage — and what to expect from each.",
  tags=["culture","guide","live"],
  body="""<p>You'll see both on Indian line-ups — some artists billed as a "DJ set," others as "live." The difference is real, and knowing it helps you pick the right night. Here's the quick version.</p>
<h2>The DJ set</h2>
<p>A DJ selects and blends existing tracks in real time, reading the crowd and building a journey out of other people's records (and often their own). The art is in the selection, the mixing and the pacing — a great DJ can take a room somewhere over hours. This is the backbone of club culture and most India nightlife.</p>
<h2>The live set</h2>
<p>A live electronic act performs their own music on the spot — using synths, drum machines, controllers and vocals to build and mutate tracks in the moment. It's less about crowd-reading flexibility and more about witnessing an artist perform their own work, often with visuals built around it. Expect something closer to a concert than a club night.</p>
<h2>Which to choose</h2>
<p>Want a long, flexible, dance-all-night journey? Go for the DJ. Want to see a specific artist perform their own music as a show? Go live. Both are brilliant — they're just different experiences, and the best festivals give you both.</p>""")

P(slug="sunrise-after-hours-culture", date="2026-03-15", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Sunrise sets and after-hours: why the best moment comes at dawn",
  excerpt="The party that refuses to end has a special magic. An ode to India's after-hours and sunrise culture.",
  tags=["after hours","sunrise","culture","guide"],
  body="""<p>Ask a seasoned party-goer for their single best dancefloor memory and there's a good chance it happened at sunrise. The after-hours session — when the crowd has thinned to the faithful and the sky starts to lighten — is where the real magic of a night lives.</p>
<h2>The dawn state</h2>
<p>Something shifts in the last hours before sunrise. The pretence falls away, the crowd is smaller and more connected, and the music — often deeper and more hypnotic by this point — hits differently. When the first light breaks over an outdoor floor, the whole room feels it at once. It's euphoric in a way peak-time never quite is.</p>
<h2>India's after-hours home</h2>
<p>Goa built its reputation on the sunrise party, and the psytrance and Himalayan scenes carry that torch — marathon sets that run from dusk clear into the next day. Even in the metros, the after-hours slot is treasured by those who know that the night's best moment often comes when most people have gone home.</p>
<h2>The advice</h2>
<p>Pace yourself, stay hydrated, and if you can, hang on for the dawn. That's when the party gives up its secrets.</p>""")

