P(slug="sunburn-festival-guide", date="2026-01-09", cat="Festival", city="Goa",
  title="Sunburn: inside Asia's biggest dance-music festival",
  excerpt="India's flagship electronic festival is a rite of passage. What Sunburn is, and how to do it right.",
  tags=["Sunburn","Goa","festival","EDM"],
  body="""<p>Sunburn is the name that put Indian dance music on the global map. Billed as one of Asia's largest electronic festivals, it has, for years, been the flagship event that introduced a generation to festival culture — and it remains a bucket-list weekend for the country's party crowd.</p>
<h2>What it is</h2>
<p>A large-scale, multi-stage electronic festival that has historically anchored the year-end season, drawing enormous crowds and a roster of the world's biggest DJs. Its heartland is Goa, whose beaches and holiday energy make the perfect backdrop, and its main stage is pure big-room spectacle — pyrotechnics, huge production, and drops you feel in your ribcage.</p>
<h2>Doing it right</h2>
<ul><li>Book accommodation and travel early — the year-end Goa surge sells out fast.</li><li>Pace yourself across the days; it's a marathon.</li><li>Explore beyond the main stage — the smaller stages often hold the deeper, more interesting sounds.</li><li>Stay hydrated, wear comfortable shoes, and plan your transport in advance.</li></ul>
<p>Whether you're a festival veteran or going for the first time, Sunburn is a defining Indian nightlife experience — go at least once.</p>""")

P(slug="vh1-supersonic-guide", date="2026-02-06", cat="Festival", city="Pune",
  title="VH1 Supersonic: the multi-genre festival that owns February",
  excerpt="Pune's marquee weekend spans techno to pop to bass. A guide to one of India's most-loved festivals.",
  tags=["VH1 Supersonic","Pune","festival"],
  body="""<p>VH1 Supersonic has grown into one of India's defining music festivals — a multi-day, multi-genre event in Pune that draws a devoted crowd every February and spans everything from underground techno to mainstream pop and heavy bass.</p>
<h2>Why it's special</h2>
<p>Supersonic's breadth is its strength. Where some festivals commit to a single sound, Supersonic curates across the spectrum — separate stages for the big-room and pop crowd, the techno and house heads, and the bass faithful. That range makes it a festival for genuine music fans, not just one tribe.</p>
<p>It's also where Pronite proudly collaborated — bringing our Udaipur energy to one of the country's biggest festival stages, a milestone we don't take lightly.</p>
<h2>Tips for the weekend</h2>
<ul><li>Study the stage schedule in advance — the clashes are real and painful.</li><li>Pune fills up on festival weekend; sort travel and stay early.</li><li>Give the underground stages your time; they're where the deep cuts live.</li></ul>
<p>For sheer variety and a passionate crowd, Supersonic is essential on the Indian festival calendar.</p>""")

P(slug="lollapalooza-india-guide", date="2026-01-22", cat="Festival", city="Mumbai",
  title="Lollapalooza India: the global giant that found a Mumbai home",
  excerpt="A legendary international festival brand, reborn in Mumbai. What to expect from India's biggest multi-genre weekend.",
  tags=["Lollapalooza","Mumbai","festival"],
  body="""<p>When a festival brand as storied as Lollapalooza set up in Mumbai, it signalled that India had arrived as a serious global music market. Its Indian edition has quickly become one of the country's premier events — a sprawling, multi-genre, multi-stage city festival held early in the year.</p>
<h2>What sets it apart</h2>
<p>Lollapalooza isn't a dance-music festival — it's an everything festival. Rock, pop, hip-hop, indie and electronic share the bill, and the line-ups pair huge international headliners with the best of India's homegrown talent. That genre-spanning approach pulls a broad, young, enthusiastic crowd and makes for a very different vibe from a pure EDM event.</p>
<h2>Planning your festival</h2>
<ul><li>It's a city festival — accommodation and transport across Mumbai need planning.</li><li>The line-up is vast; map your must-sees against the stage times early.</li><li>Come for the discovery — the undercard often outshines the headliners.</li></ul>
<p>For range, scale and a genuine festival atmosphere, Lollapalooza India is a January highlight worth building a trip around.</p>""")

P(slug="nh7-weekender-guide", date="2026-03-11", cat="Festival", city="India",
  title="NH7 Weekender: 'the happiest music festival' and India's indie heart",
  excerpt="A multi-city institution built on indie, rock and eclectic line-ups. A guide to the beloved NH7 Weekender.",
  tags=["NH7 Weekender","indie","festival"],
  body="""<p>Long before the big-room EDM wave, NH7 Weekender was building India's live-music festival culture — and it's still one of the most loved events in the country. Nicknamed "the happiest music festival," it's built on eclectic, genre-spanning line-ups with a big heart for indie and rock.</p>
<h2>The character</h2>
<p>NH7 Weekender is a curator's festival. Rather than chasing the biggest EDM names, it champions independent artists, rock bands, hip-hop, fusion and electronic acts side by side, often across multiple cities. The result is a warm, discovery-driven atmosphere that die-hard music fans adore — less spectacle, more substance.</p>
<h2>Why it endures</h2>
<p>In a scene that can chase trends, NH7 has stayed true to a vision: great music across genres, a friendly crowd, and a platform for homegrown talent. It's a festival that helped build careers and shape tastes across a generation of Indian music lovers.</p>
<h2>The tip</h2>
<p>Go in open-minded and wander between stages. NH7's magic is in the acts you didn't come for but leave obsessed with.</p>""")

P(slug="magnetic-fields-guide", date="2026-01-30", cat="Festival", city="Rajasthan",
  title="Magnetic Fields: a boutique festival in a Rajasthan palace",
  excerpt="Electronic music, art and a 17th-century fort under desert stars. Inside India's most atmospheric boutique festival.",
  tags=["Magnetic Fields","Rajasthan","festival","boutique"],
  body="""<p>If the mega-festivals aren't your speed, Magnetic Fields might be your perfect weekend. Held at a heritage palace-fort in rural Rajasthan, it's a boutique electronic-and-arts festival famous for its extraordinary setting, thoughtful curation and intimate scale.</p>
<h2>The setting is the star</h2>
<p>There's nothing quite like dancing in the courtyards and ramparts of a centuries-old Rajasthani fort, with desert skies overhead and a sound system tuned for the underground. Magnetic Fields pairs that setting with carefully chosen electronic line-ups, art installations, secret stages and a crowd that comes for the whole experience, not just the headliners.</p>
<h2>The vibe</h2>
<p>Boutique means intimate — smaller crowds, a strong sense of community, and a design-forward, immersive atmosphere that the big festivals can't match. It's become a favourite for the discerning end of India's scene, and its Rajasthan home gives it a magic our own Udaipur events know well.</p>
<h2>Planning</h2>
<ul><li>It's remote — travel and accommodation are part of the adventure; plan ahead.</li><li>Desert nights get cold; pack layers.</li><li>Embrace the full experience — the art and the setting are half the point.</li></ul>
<p>For atmosphere over scale, few festivals in the world compare.</p>""")

P(slug="echoes-of-earth-guide", date="2026-02-25", cat="Festival", city="Bengaluru",
  title="Echoes of Earth: India's greenest music festival",
  excerpt="Sustainability meets serious music near Bengaluru. A guide to the eco-conscious festival with a devoted following.",
  tags=["Echoes of Earth","Bengaluru","festival","sustainability"],
  body="""<p>Echoes of Earth has carved out a unique place in India's festival landscape as the country's flagship eco-conscious music event. Held near Bengaluru, it pairs a thoughtfully curated line-up with a genuine commitment to sustainability — proof that a festival can have a conscience and still throw a great party.</p>
<h2>The concept</h2>
<p>Everything about Echoes of Earth is designed with the environment in mind — from stages and art built with recycled and natural materials to a strong sustainability ethos woven through the whole event. The music leans toward the organic, earthy end of electronic and live acts, matching the festival's spirit.</p>
<h2>The crowd</h2>
<p>Bengaluru's famously discerning music audience is the perfect home for a festival like this. The crowd is engaged, conscious and there for a curated experience rather than a big-room spectacle — one of the most pleasant festival atmospheres in the country.</p>
<h2>Why it matters</h2>
<p>As India's festival scene grows, events like Echoes of Earth set an important example: that scale and responsibility aren't mutually exclusive. It's a festival to support and to enjoy in equal measure.</p>""")

P(slug="ragasthan-desert-festival", date="2026-03-01", cat="Festival", city="Rajasthan",
  title="Ragasthan: camping and music in the Thar Desert",
  excerpt="A remote desert festival built on adventure, camping and eclectic sound. For the party-goer who wants to escape.",
  tags=["Ragasthan","desert","camping","festival"],
  body="""<p>Ragasthan takes the festival experience about as far off the grid as India offers — a camping-and-music event set amid the dunes of the Thar Desert, built for those who want their party wrapped in genuine adventure.</p>
<h2>The experience</h2>
<p>This is a festival where getting there is part of the story. Deep in the Rajasthani desert, Ragasthan blends live and electronic music with camping under vast open skies, adventure activities, and the raw beauty of the dunes. It's less about headliners and more about the whole immersive escape — the kind of festival you feel changed by.</p>
<h2>The Rajasthan connection</h2>
<p>As an Udaipur collective, we have a soft spot for events that use Rajasthan's landscape as their canvas. The desert setting gives Ragasthan an atmosphere no urban festival can replicate — starfields, silence, and a dancefloor in the middle of nowhere.</p>
<h2>Know before you go</h2>
<ul><li>It's remote and rugged — come prepared for desert camping conditions.</li><li>Days are hot, nights are cold; pack accordingly.</li><li>Embrace the adventure mindset; this isn't a city festival.</li></ul>
<p>For the traveller-partier, Ragasthan is a genuine bucket-list experience.</p>""")

P(slug="zomaland-guide", date="2026-03-19", cat="Festival", city="India",
  title="Zomaland: the food-and-music carnival touring India's cities",
  excerpt="Part festival, part food carnival, all family-friendly fun. A guide to the multi-city Zomaland experience.",
  tags=["Zomaland","food","festival","family"],
  body="""<p>Not every festival is a late-night rave. Zomaland is a daytime carnival of food, music and entertainment that tours multiple Indian cities, offering a family-friendly, all-ages festival experience built around the country's greatest love: eating.</p>
<h2>The concept</h2>
<p>Zomaland combines a huge spread of food stalls from popular restaurants with live music, comedy, carnival games and entertainment across a day-long event. It's accessible, upbeat and designed for a broad audience — friends, families, couples — rather than the dedicated clubbing crowd.</p>
<h2>Why it's clever</h2>
<p>By marrying food (the one thing every Indian gathering revolves around) with music and entertainment, Zomaland found a format that pulls a crowd well beyond the usual festival demographic. It tours widely, bringing the experience to cities that don't always get the big music festivals.</p>
<h2>The read</h2>
<p>If you want festival energy without the late-night commitment — or a day out that works for a mixed group — Zomaland is a genuinely fun option, and a smart example of how India's event scene keeps broadening its appeal.</p>""")

P(slug="hornbill-festival-guide", date="2026-01-13", cat="Festival", city="Nagaland",
  title="Hornbill Festival: culture, music and the Northeast's grandest gathering",
  excerpt="More cultural extravaganza than club night, Nagaland's Hornbill Festival is a bucket-list Indian experience.",
  tags=["Hornbill","Nagaland","culture","festival"],
  body="""<p>India's festival calendar isn't only dancefloors, and the Hornbill Festival proves it. Held in Nagaland, this celebrated cultural extravaganza showcases the traditions, food, crafts and music of the Northeast's tribes — with a genuinely rocking music component that surprises first-timers.</p>
<h2>What it is</h2>
<p>Often called the "Festival of Festivals," Hornbill brings together Nagaland's diverse communities for a multi-day celebration of indigenous culture — traditional dance, ceremonies, cuisine and crafts. Alongside the cultural programme runs a music dimension, including a famous rock contest that has become a launchpad for regional bands.</p>
<h2>Why go</h2>
<p>Hornbill is a window into one of India's most fascinating and least-visited regions. For the traveller who wants their music wrapped in deep cultural experience — and a landscape of stunning hills — it's unforgettable. The Northeast has one of the country's richest live-music cultures, and Hornbill is its showcase.</p>
<h2>Planning</h2>
<ul><li>It's a journey to reach — build a proper Northeast trip around it.</li><li>Winter timing means cool weather; pack warm.</li><li>Come for the culture as much as the music.</li></ul>
<p>A completely different kind of festival — and all the more special for it.</p>""")

P(slug="ziro-festival-guide", date="2026-01-27", cat="Festival", city="Arunachal Pradesh",
  title="Ziro Festival of Music: indie bliss in a Himalayan valley",
  excerpt="Rolling rice fields, pine hills and independent music — Ziro is India's most idyllic outdoor festival.",
  tags=["Ziro","Arunachal","indie","festival"],
  body="""<p>Tucked away in a picture-perfect valley in Arunachal Pradesh, the Ziro Festival of Music is India's most idyllic outdoor gathering — an independent-music festival set among rolling rice fields and pine-covered hills, far from the noise of the metros.</p>
<h2>The setting and sound</h2>
<p>Ziro is a celebration of independent music, hosting homegrown and international indie, rock, folk and electronic acts on open-air stages framed by some of the most beautiful scenery in the country. The scale is intimate, the pace unhurried, and the emphasis firmly on discovery and community over spectacle.</p>
<h2>The experience</h2>
<p>Getting to Ziro is an adventure through the Northeast's hills, and that remoteness is exactly what makes it special. The crowd camps, connects and immerses in both the music and the local Apatani culture. It's less a festival you attend than a place you go to reset.</p>
<h2>Tips</h2>
<ul><li>Plan the journey carefully — it's remote and reaching it takes time.</li><li>Camp and embrace the slow pace; that's the point.</li><li>Respect the local community and environment.</li></ul>
<p>For indie lovers and travellers alike, Ziro is a once-in-a-lifetime kind of festival.</p>""")

P(slug="mahindra-blues-guide", date="2026-02-13", cat="Festival", city="Mumbai",
  title="Mahindra Blues: India's home of the blues",
  excerpt="Asia's biggest blues festival brings legends to Mumbai every February. A guide for the roots-music faithful.",
  tags=["Mahindra Blues","Mumbai","blues","festival"],
  body="""<p>For lovers of roots music, February in Mumbai means one thing: the Mahindra Blues Festival, billed as one of Asia's largest celebrations of the blues. It's a reminder that India's festival culture reaches far beyond electronic and Bollywood.</p>
<h2>What it offers</h2>
<p>Mahindra Blues brings international blues legends and rising talent to an iconic Mumbai venue for a weekend of soulful, guitar-driven, deeply felt music. The atmosphere is intimate and reverent — a crowd of genuine music heads there to witness masters of a storied genre, not to rave.</p>
<h2>Why it matters</h2>
<p>The festival has done enormous work in nurturing an appreciation for the blues in India, bringing acts that fans would otherwise never see live and giving the country's own blues and roots musicians a marquee platform. It's a labour of love that has become a fixture of the Mumbai calendar.</p>
<h2>The read</h2>
<p>If your idea of a great night is a searing guitar solo rather than a bass drop, Mahindra Blues is your festival. Soulful, world-class, and unlike anything else on the Indian calendar.</p>""")

P(slug="best-holi-parties-india", date="2026-03-09", cat="Festival", city="India",
  title="The best Holi parties in India: a city-by-city guide",
  excerpt="Where to throw colour to the best soundtrack — a rundown of India's biggest and best Holi celebrations.",
  tags=["Holi","festival","pool party","guide"],
  body="""<p>Holi has become the single biggest party moment on India's calendar, and every major city now throws a flagship colour celebration. Here's a guide to where the festival of colours goes hardest — and how to pick your perfect Holi.</p>
<h2>The big-city blowouts</h2>
<p><b>Delhi-NCR</b> hosts some of the largest, most star-studded Holi festivals in the country — huge crowds, big-name performers, and full festival production. <b>Mumbai and Pune</b> excel at the rain-dance-and-DJ format, packing venues with colour, water and non-stop music.</p>
<h2>The scenic sessions</h2>
<p><b>Goa</b> gives Holi a beachside spin, while <b>Rajasthan</b> — Jaipur and Udaipur — pairs the festival with heritage and lakeside settings. Our own Rangilo Rajasthan pool party at The Udaisarovar is built exactly for this: organic colour, a lakeside deck, rain showers and a festival-house soundtrack.</p>
<h2>How to choose</h2>
<ul><li>Want scale and star power? Head to a Delhi mega-festival.</li><li>Want a scenic, boutique vibe? Rajasthan and Goa deliver.</li><li>Always check for organic, skin-friendly colours — the good events insist on them.</li></ul>
<p>Wherever you play, Holi is India's most joyful party. Pick your city and dive in.</p>""")

P(slug="india-festival-calendar-2026", date="2026-01-06", cat="Festival", city="India",
  title="The India music festival calendar: a year-round guide",
  excerpt="From Sunburn in December to Ziro in autumn — how India's festival season actually flows across the year.",
  tags=["festival","calendar","guide","2026"],
  body="""<p>India's festival scene isn't a single season — it's a year-round rhythm shaped by weather, holidays and geography. Here's how the calendar actually flows, so you can plan your year around the events that matter.</p>
<h2>Winter: the peak (November–February)</h2>
<p>The cool, dry months are prime time. The year-end brings the biggest names and the Goa surge around Sunburn and New Year's. January delivers Mumbai's giant city festival; February belongs to Pune's multi-genre weekend and Mumbai's blues gathering. Boutique gems in Rajasthan light up the desert. This is the heart of the season.</p>
<h2>Spring: colour and heat (March–April)</h2>
<p>Holi turns the whole country into a party in March, and pool-party season opens as the heat builds. The touring-artist circuit runs hard before the monsoon.</p>
<h2>Summer &amp; monsoon: the pivot (May–September)</h2>
<p>The plains empty out and the scene heads to the Himalayan hills for cool-climate raves, then retreats indoors as the monsoon arrives. A quieter, club-driven stretch.</p>
<h2>Autumn: the reawakening (October onward)</h2>
<p>As the rains clear, the festival machine roars back — Northeast gems like Ziro and Hornbill, and the long build toward another year-end crescendo.</p>
<p>Plan around the season, and India will keep you dancing all year.</p>""")
